						<!-- surphace start --><p style="text-align: center"><img class="size-full wp-image-7283 aligncenter" src="http://gadgetcrave.frsucrave.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/nextep.jpg" alt="nextep Sony Nextep: Flexible OLED Wristop Computer Design " width="563" height="372" title="Sony Nextep: Flexible OLED Wristop Computer Design " /></p>
<p>Just a few decades ago, the idea of traveling wherever you go with a computer in tow was a foreign one. Two decades ago, you would have gotten strange looks if you described a magazine-sized computer that&#8217;s essentially a big, reactive monitor. Perhaps, designer Hiromi Kiriki is on to something similarly prophetic with the Sony Nextep wrist computer. The name of the concept certainly indicates that he thinks so.</p>
<p><span id="more-7282"></span></p>
<p>While tablets are convenient, who would really lug around a large, stiff brick of a computer when they could enjoy a flexible computer that attaches to the wrist? With flexible OLED technology, Kiriki envisions a super adjustable type of portable computer with a thin, pull-out keyboard and wrist-wrapping design. The design also includes a holographic projector to add a little extra space to the OLED touchscreen when needed. Seeing how OLED technology is advancing, perhaps we&#8217;ll see a device like this within the 2020 timeframe that Kiriki designates. I wish this design actually came from Sony (or any manufacturer) because I&#8217;d definitely buy one. [<a href="http://www.yankodesign.com/2010/05/25/in-2020-we-can-wear-sony-computers-on-our-wrist/">Yanko </a>via <a href="http://dvice.com/archives/2010/05/could-this-be-t-1.php">Dvice</a>]</p>

